{
  "texts": [
    "Likewise, the maximal revenue the platform can collect from the firms (and specifically from the naïfs) is given by m * (α (L), α (R)) ≤ L ϕ (1 2 -ϕ)(α (L) +α (R)) for some constant L ϕ > 0, as we did in the proof of Proposition 14 in Acemoglu, Huttenlocher, Ozdaglar, and Siderius (2024).",
    "To see this, one can just let L ϕ to be defined as the maximal change in advertising revenue following a decrease in the technology ϕ, i.e., L ϕ = max ϕ∈[0,1/2] |∂m * (α (L) * (ϕ, λ), α (R) * (ϕ, λ))/∂ϕ| < R. For φ = 1 2 -T /L ϕ, if ϕ ′ > φ, then the platform opts for a fully subscription-based business model instead, leading to the same effect as with λ ′ > λ, following from Lemma 1(ii).",
    "Additionally, digital ad taxes that shift platforms toward a subscription-based model, discussed in detail inAcemoglu,",
    "The case where r1 ̸ = r2 will lead to fundamentally similar insights, but the distribution of beliefs after the articles are recommended, H, will depend on the difference between r1 and r2.",
    "Since we are interested in the role AI plays in its recommendation algorithm, we simplify along this dimension and focus on articles that have similar likelihood to contain misinformation."
  ]
}